Above I inadvertently miss-spelled Charlie King's name (clicked the wrong button on the spelling checker).  <br><br>
SSgt. Charles King was lost on December 25th, 1968 trying to rescue a pilot who was still in his harness.  It was a trap, and when he was hit, Charlie radioed the Jolly Green above him to get out of there.  The helicopter was taking hits when it departed, tearing the hoist from its mount before the hoist cable snapped (it was tangled in trees below after Charlie had been lowered for the rescue attempt).  <br><br>
Charlie King was never heard from again.  He was listed MIA, and officially declared KIA on December 5th, 1978.  He was awarded the Air Force Cross posthumously.  <br><br>
I have a case with my beret and some patches displayed on it.  Below, screwed into the frame, is the POW/MIA bracelet with Charlie's name on it.  I wore it during the 1970's, until the chrome finish had disappeared on its back.  <br><br>
Charlie and I were in the same graduating class, and from time to time when I think it is appropriate I'll continue to bring up his name.  He will not be forgotten, and his deeds will not be diminished.
